[[File:Dacian Gold Bracelet at the National Museum of Romanian History 2011 - 5.jpg|thumb|290px|right|Dacian gold bracelet, dated to the 1st century BC or 1st century AD, from [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmizegetusa]] [[Romania]] {{sfn|Trohani|2007|p=5}}{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2010|p=1040}}]]
[[File:Bratarile Dacice IMG 7303.JPG|thumb|right|Dacians gold bracelet from Sarmizegetusa Regia, dated the 1st century BC or 1st century AD {{sfn|Trohani|2007|p=1}}]]
[[File:Tezaur MNIR IMG 7280.JPG|thumb|right|Dacian gold bracelet from [[Cucuteni|Baiceni]] dated to the 4th century BC ([[Iași County]]){{sfn|Arbunescu|2011|p=1}}]]

The '''Dacian bracelets''' are [[bracelets]] associated with the ancient people known as the [[Dacians]], a distinct branch of the [[Thracians]]. These bracelets were used as ornaments, [[currency]], high rank insignia and [[votive offerings]]<ref><ol class="references">
For the various functions of bracelets with Dacians see Florescu et. al (1980) p.68
* For the high rank insignia, see Sîrbu and Florea (2000) p.13
* For the bracelets used as ornaments, see Dumitrescu H (1941), p.137
* For the votive offerings see Spânu (1998) p.49
* For the bracelet-currency see Popescu (1956) p.212
* For the North Thracians see McHenry Encyclopædia Britannica (1993) p.602
</ol></ref> Their ornamentations consist of many elaborate regionally distinct styles.{{sfn|Taylor|2001|p=212}} Bracelets of various types were worn by Dacians, but the most characteristic piece of their jewelry was the large multi-spiral bracelets; engraved with [[palmette]]s towards the ends and terminating in the shape of an animal head, usually that of a snake.{{sfn|Popescu|1971|p=45}}

== Dacians background ==
[[File:Muzeuldeistorienaturalavienaaurdacic7.JPG|thumb|right|Spiral motif with gold bracelet found in Romania (dated to Bronze IV = Hallstatt A){{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=57}}) repository [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]]{{sfn|Burda |1979|p=17}}]]
[[File:Muzeuldeistorienaturalavienaaurdacic5Pipea.JPG|thumb|right|Horn motif with gold bracelet from [[Pipea]] ([[Mureș County]]) dated to Hallstatt period {{sfn|Şandric|2008|p=2}} or to Bronze Age {{sfn|Mozsolics|1970|p=143}} ]]

The [[Dacians]] lived in a very large territory, stretching from the [[Balkans]] to the northern [[Carpathians]] and from the [[Black Sea]] and the [[Nistru|Tyras River (Nistru)]] to the [[Tisza|Tisa]] plain, and at times as far as the [[Middle Danube]].{{sfn|MacKenzie|1986|p=25}}

[[Dacian civilization]] went through several stages of development, from the [[Thracian]] stage in the [[Bronze Age]] to the [[Geto-Dacian stage]] in the classical period that lasted from the 1st century BC to the 1st century AD.{{sfn|Giurescu|Nestorescu|1981|p=47}} The Thracian stage is associated with the emergence of Thracian populations from the fusion of the local [[Eneolithic|Chalcolithic]] stock with the incoming peoples of the transitional Indo-Europeanization Period.{{sfn|Dumitrescu|Boardman|1982|p=53}}{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=52}} By the time of [[Bronze Age]], and during the transitional period to the [[Iron Age]], the cultures of this Carpathian area may be attributed to proto-Thracian and even Thracian populations—ancestors of the peoples known to Herodotus as the Agathyrsae and the Getae, and to the Romans as the [[Dacians]] (by Iron Age II).{{sfn|Cunliffe|1987|p=59}}{{sfn|Dumitrescu|1972|p=259}} The culture of these nuclear groups were typified by military aristocracies.{{sfn|McHenry|Encyclopædia Britannica | 1993|p=602}}

In these early times the most specific motifs of the bracelets are the spiral and the horn, used to provide the warrior with both physical and deistic protection.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=57}}
* The ''spiral motif'' (i.e. bracelets from [[Sacosu Mare]], [[Şagu|Firighiaz (now Firiteaz)]], [[Săcueni]]) is associated with solar cults.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=53}}{{sfn|Burda|1979|p=17}} It might have been an inheritance of the local Chalcolithic culture,{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=57}} or an accentuated [[Mycenaean Greece|Mycenaean]] influence to the north of the Danube.{{sfn|Dumitrescu|1972|p=258}}
* The ''horn motifs'' (i.e. bracelets from [[Pipea]], [[Şona|Biia (Şona)]], [[Şeica Mare|Boarta (Şeica Mare)]]) might have been brought by the [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|intrusive stockbreeders (Proto-Indo-Europeans)]].{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=57}}

The 5th century BC is associated with the Dacian stage of art{{sfn|Megaw| 1970| p=32}}{{sfn|Sandars| 1976|p=51}} and it is the time of the [[La Tène]] period (Iron Age II) when Dacian culture flourished, especially in Transylvanian citadels.{{sfn|McKendrick|1975|p=19}} The Dacian art of Iron Age II has all the characteristics of a mixed style, with its roots in the [[Hallstatt culture]] (1200–500 BC).{{sfn|Halbertsma|1994|p=26}}{{sfn|McKendrick|1975|p=19}} It is characterized by an accentuated geometry, a curvilinear style and plant-based motifs.{{sfn|Taylor|2001|p=212}} At this time, besides their older local types, Dacians made all kind of bracelets that were common in the [[Roman Empire]].{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|p=25}} But, there was a constant preference of Dacians for decorating the silver spiral bracelets with animals [[protome]] such as snakes and wolves.{{sfn|Sîrbu|Florea|2000|p=69}}

The period of time between the 2nd century BC and 1st century AD is termed "Classic Dacian".{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=63}} At this time the Dacians developed the art of silverworking, and a style which may be described specifically as the Dacian style. It consists of older traditional local elements, dating back to Iron Age I, but also of elements of Celtic, Scythian, Thracian, and especially Greek origins.{{sfn|Popescu|1959|p=22}}{{sfn|Halbertsma|1994|p=26}} The bracelets of this art-form include silver arm rings, with ends in the shape of stylized heads of animals, and heavy spiral-shaped armlets with gilded ends adorned with palm-leaves, and ending in animal-heads.{{sfn|Popescu|1959|p=22}}

The Classic Dacian period ends when parts of the [[Dacian State]] were reduced to a Roman province by the [[Roman Empire]] under [[Trajan]], partly in order to seize its [[gold mines]]. After the [[Second Dacian War]] (105–106 AD) Romans claimed they had looted 165 tonnes of gold and 300 tonnes of silver in a single [[wikt:haul|haul]], as estimated by modern historians. Its existence in only one spot (at Sarmizegethusa), suggests that there was a central control of precious metal circulation.{{sfn|Taylor|1994|p=406}} According to the majority of historians this sort of monopoly of precious metals, and the Roman's forcible collection of Dacian gold objects, explains the scarcity of archaeological discoveries consisting of golden ornaments for the period between the 3rd century BC and the 1st century AD;{{sfn|Seculici|2008|p=67}}{{sfn|Manaila|1976|p=90}} however, the existence of the "[[Treasures of Dacian kings]]" has been confirmed by the latest archaeological finds of large gold spiral-shaped bracelets from [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmizegetusa]]. It seems that the Romans did not find the entire royal treasure.{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2007|p=32}}{{sfn|Glodariu|Sima|Iaroslavschi|Gheorghiu|2008|p=146}}

== Bracelets in the transition period North Thracian and proto-Dacian ==
===Types of bracelets in the Bronze Age and First Iron Age===
Numerous bracelets were made of bronze and gold and many of them have been found in Transylvania, near the sources of the ores used in their manufacture.{{sfn|Coles|Harding|1979 |p=94}} They include the following types:
* unequally spiraled armlet made of bronze, worn on the forearm that is also called "arm guard" i.e. those found at Apa ([[Satu Mare County]]){{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}}
* equally spiraled bracelet, used frequently in the early Hallstatt i.e. [[Pecica]].{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}}
* open bracelet with widened ends, made of double gold wire i.e. [[Ostrovu Mare|Ostrovu Mare (Gogoşu)]].{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}}
* bracelet with spiralled or volutes endings i.e. [[Şagu|Firighiaz/Firiteaz]],{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}} [[Darova|Sacoșu Mare]].{{sfn|Leahu|2004|p=1}}
* open bracelet decorated with incisions, with each end coiled in double opposed volutes i.e. [[Darova|Sacoșu Mare]] and Hodiş ([[Bihor County]]).{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}}
* overlapped ends, rhombic cross section i.e. [[Darova|Sacoșu Mare]] and [[Şmig]].{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}} The treasures from Şmig [[Sibiu County]] and from [[Boroşneu Mare|Ţufalău (Boroşneu Mare)]] contained also raw gold, thus suggesting the bracelets had been locally made.{{sfn| Popescu | 1956|p= 227}}

Some bronze bracelet types of the Bronze Age (i.e. incised solid bracelets) continue throughout all the Late Bronze Age and Hallstatt phases.{{sfn|Coles|Harding|1979|p=409}}

