File:Bracelet Dacia left bank Lower Danube.jpg|Dacian bracelet from North of Danube (unknown find spot).{{sfn|Linas|1888|p=288}}
</gallery>

Bronze bracelets of this type had previously been found in deposits belonging to the first Hallstatt period. Their ornamentation and groups of motifs is similar to the Firighiaz (Firiteaz) type. Analogous bracelets had also been found at [[Oradea]].{{sfn| Popescu | 1956|p= 215}} Two bracelets with spiral ends, dated to the Iron Age, have also been found in Dacian tombs of the Lower Danube.{{sfn|Linas|1887|p=288}}

=== "Horn motif" from Pipea, Biia and Boarta ===
[[File:Dacian goblet from Biia.jpg|thumb|right|The golden goblet from Biia with twin spiral terminals of the handles.{{sfn| Hoddinott |1989|p=53}}]]
Bracelets from [[Şona|Biia]] and [[Pipea]], found in the 19th century, have an unclear chronology.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=239}} This series comprises a find from [[Abrud]] and another from an unknown [[Transylvania]]n location.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=59}} Some archaeologists are reporting them as dating to the Hallstatt,{{sfn|Şandric|2003|p=2}}{{sfn|Şandric|2008|p=2}} though Márton (1933) dated them to the early La Tene period.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=222}} Popescu (1956) estimates these can be dated to the Hallstat phase B (1000–800 BC), but no later than C (800–650 BC).{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=239}} whereas Mozsolics (1970) dates them to 1,500 BC.{{sfn|Mozsolics|1970|p=143}} The so-called Biia bracelet was found with the Biia gold "[[kantharos]]" that can be dated between 1,500 and 1,000 BC.{{sfn|Eluère|1991|p=7o}} The handles of this goblet are also coiled into a double-spiral motif similar to other types of bracelets from the Carpathian area (i.e. Firigiaz 3, or Acas-Sacueni).{{sfn|Bouzek |1985|p=52}}

There, specimens are made of bronze and are prototypes of the Pipea–Biia–Boarta series of bracelets; therefore, scholars agree these bracelets had been made locally, in the Transylvanian goldsmith workshops. This opinion is supported by metal analysis.{{sfn|Kovacs|2001|p=48}}

These types of bracelets are possibly [[votive offering]]s, reminiscent of the [[Bull (mythology)|cult of the bull]].{{sfn|Eluère|1987|p=76}} Their common trait is the stylized motif of "horns". All of them have large C-shaped "horns" as terminals.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=59}}  As with the spiral, Hoddinott purports that the east-central European bronzesmiths used this horn symbol to provide the warrior with both physical and deistic protection.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=58}} In the Aegean Shaft Graves it occurs only on a stele, a gold bowl and three pairs of gold earrings, which Hoddinott considers to be possibly of central European origin.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=59}} This thematic motif of the Carpathian peoples is confirmed by other archaeological finds from Transylvania that include three large rings weighing between 0.20 kilograms (0.44 pounds) and 0.60 kilograms (1.32 pounds). Their terminals are animal heads facing each other, depicting the heads of horses in two cases and bulls-heads in the third.{{sfn|Eluère|1987|p=58}} Eluere (1987) identifies the endings of the Pipea-Biia bracelets with the cultic and religious powerful horns of the bull, and estimates that this myth was perpetuated for centuries.{{sfn|Eluère|1987|p=58}}

<gallery>
File:Dacian gold bracelet finds Biia Magyarbenye.jpg|Gold bracelet found at Biia Romania; dated to Hallstatt; National Museum, Budapest Hungary{{sfn|Hampel|1881|p=214-216}}
File:Prehistoric Transylvania Dacia bracelet.jpg|Bracelet from unknown Transylvania findspot{{sfn|Hampel|1881|p=214-216}} It belongs to the series of bracelets from Pipea – Biia – Boarta
File:Solid_gold_bracelet_from_Pipea_(Dacia).jpg|Solid gold bracelet from [[Pipea]] Romania, dated to Hallstatt{{sfn|Şandric|2008|p=2}}
File:Decorative motifs bracelets Pipea Biia and Karasz Dacia.jpg|Decorative motifs of bracelets from Biia-Pipea{{sfn| Hampel |1881|pp=214–216}}
File:Muzeuldeistorienaturalavienaaurdacic.JPG|Dacian bracelets found in Transylvania Romania – reposited by [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] Vienna
</gallery>

According to Hoddinott (1989), [[Horned deity|the horned animal cults]] that are attested with these horns motifs were brought by the transitional Indo-Europeanization period immigrants who adopted these stylized motifs as their main apotropaic symbol;{{sfn|Hoddinott|1989|p=57}} however, the symbols of the horned animal replaced the local ones but were later associated with the sun-fire symbols of the earlier culture.{{sfn|Hoddinott|1981|p=165}}

The bracelet from [[Bilje]] (Croatia) belongs to the same Biia-Pipea type.{{sfn|Eluère|1987|p=76}}  Hartmann noted that the percentage of silver and tin in the bracelets from Belly (Croatia) and Pipea (Romania) is almost identical. This suggests both bracelets had been made in the same region.{{sfn|Kovacs|2001|p=48}} According to Marton, the armlets with semi-moon ends are part of an evolutionary series that terminates with the later silver snake-headed bracelets of the Classical Dacian times.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=222}}

==== Boarta type ====
The bracelet from [[Şeica Mare|Boarta (Şeica Mare-Sibiu County)]] was discovered in 1891 and is dated to 600 BC. It might be an example of the last phases in the evolution of the Biia-Pipea gold artifacts (For the photo of Boarta bracelet see the gallery of links {{sfn|Wittenberger|2010|p=1}}) A very similar copy of the Boarta type has been found with the treasure from [[Dalj]], [[Slavonia]].{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=217}}

Unlike the Biia-Pipe type bracelets, the Boarta bracelet is flat, band-shaped, and has three raised ribs resembling the body of two other bracelets from [[Oradea]]. Its semi moon-shape terminals are smaller than the Biia-Pipea terminals;{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=217}} thus, some scholars derive the type of the Boarta bracelet to be from some earlier bronze bracelets whose ends widen and whose bodies have more ridges.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=221}}

It seems that some other bracelets found at [[Bihor County|Bihor]], Oradea, [[Targu Mures]] and [[Timiș County|Făget]] could possibly belong to the Boarta type, and not to the Biia-Pipea type.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=217}}

<gallery>
File:Muzeuldeistorienaturalavienaaurdacic6Pipea.JPG|Gold bracelet from [[Bilje]] in today [[Croatia]] part of the Biia-Pipea series dated to Hallstatt{{sfn|Eluère|1991|p=76}}
File:Dacian type bracelet from Dalj.jpg|Boarta's very similar type found at [[Dalj]] ([[Slavonia]]){{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=217}}
File:Gold Dacian bracelet Hallstatt Mojna.jpg|''Mosna 1'' – A Dacian gold bracelet dated to the Hallstatt period. [[Moşna, Sibiu|Moşna]], [[Sibiu County]]{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=345}}
</gallery>

==== Mosna, Sibiu County ====
The terminal adornments of this gold bracelet look like animals' heads, but the zoomorphic motif almost disappeared because of the geometric stylization (see picture ''Mosna 1'' above). It is dated to the Hallstatt period. This is not an isolated item, since it is stylistically connected to the geometric and zoomorphism of a collar and two bracelets from [[Veliki Gaj]] (Hungarian Nagygáj, Romanian Gaiu Mare) in Serbia.{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=345}}

== Zoomorphic bracelets ==
[[File:Muzeuldeistorienaturalavienaaurdacic4brasov.JPG|thumb|right|Gold bracelet with horse heads from [[Vad-Făgăraș]], [[Brașov County]] at [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]], Vienna.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=221}}{{sfn|Coles|Harding|1979|p=366}}]]
In the past, on the basis of a relatively small selection of archaeological finds, some scholars considered that the art of Geto-Dacians was geometrical and non-iconic. This led to the zoomorphic representations of Dacian bracelets being seen as an expression of the art of the steppes people, and Scythian art in particular. The majority of archaeological finds to date show that the main aspect of Geto-Dacian [[toreutics]] is in fact a zoomorphic motif style of its own.{{sfn|Gramatopol |1992|p=1}} This Dacian style of animal art occurs at the time when various ancient historical sources begin to record the Geto-Dacians as an ethnic entity of the larger Thracian family; therefore, this artistic expression might be considered as specific to the Dacian society of the last centuries BC.{{sfn|Gramatopol |1992|p=1}}

Some scholars sustain that the zoomorphic motifs of that particular time do not represent any kind of zoolatry of the Geto-Dacians. These would be iconographic motifs highlighting and multiplying certain attributes of the deities or of the kings.{{sfn| Sarbu| Florea |2000|p=152}}

=== Ox-headed bracelets (Târgu Mureş, Apoldu de Sus, Vad) ===
The tendency towards the apotropaic zoomorphism that crystallized at the end of the Iron Age I (i.e. bracelets from Biia, Pipea, Boarta etc.) is clearly manifested with the bracelets possessing ornamented ox heads of the Iron Age II (La Tene) from [[Târgu Mureş]] (Mureş County), [[Apoldu de Sus]] (Sibiu County), [[Şercaia|Vad]] (Braşov County) and one from an unknown Transylvanian find.{{sfn|Sanie|1995|p=24}} The bracelet from Apoldu de Sus seems to have an ox head at one terminus and a ram's head at the other end.{{sfn| Popescu | 1956|p= 218}}

The ox-head bracelets have been associated with the clay Hallstatian's [[Moon idol]], with which they  undoubtedly share a similarity.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=221}}

The wires of these series of bracelets are thick, and decorated with ornamental protrusions.{{sfn| Popescu | 1956|p= 218}} Their characteristic decor consists of [[relief]] or incised circles, while there are also those with cuts or incisions that form a fir-tree motif.{{sfn|Sanie|1995|p=24}}

A bracelet with ox-heads discovered in the 19th century at Târgu Mureş (see [http://www.lessing-photo.com/dispimg.asp?i=07020269+&cr=44&cl=1 picture]) had been dated by some scholars to La Tene.{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=546}} Others such as Popescu (1956) dated this particular one to the last period of the Hallstatt, since it might have been deposited together with a semi-moon type bracelet of that period.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=239}} As for the technique, it is noted that the bracelet from Targu Mures show a control of three-dimensional modeling,{{sfn|Sherratt|1984|pp=22, 23}} with silver inlays.{{sfn|Popescu|1950|p=28}} There are two other bracelets of a similar type in the Transylvania Museum, though they are known to be discovered in Transylvania the original site is unknown.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=217}}

The religious meaning of the sacred horn had been lost over time, the circlets keeping this shape can only be described as decorative ornamentation.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=221}} The bracelet found in 1817 at Vad–Fagaras (Brasov County) terminating with horse heads depicted as wearing a bridle, is part of the general trend of bracelets replacing the sacred horn as a motif.{{sfn|Popescu|1956|p=221}}{{sfn|Macrea|1978|p=197}}

=== Băiceni bracelets ===
{{multiple image|width=200|direction=vertical
|image1=Dacian_Gold_Bracelet_at_the_National_Museum_of_Romanian_History_2011_-_2.jpg|caption1=Dacian gold bracelet [[Cucuteni|Băiceni (Cucuteni)]], 4th century BC{{sfn|Arbunescu|2011|p=1}}
|image2=MNIR Dacian Bracelet 2011. Detail.JPG|caption2=''Head 1'' – Detail of one of the zoomorphic bracelets from [[Cucuteni|Băiceni (Cucuteni)]], 4th century BC{{sfn|Sîrbu|2004|p=150}}
}}
In 1959 two bracelets terminating with "horned-horses", were found at [[Cucuteni|Băiceni (Cucuteni)]].{{sfn|Sanie|1995|p=151}} They are dated to the end of the Iron Age I{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}} and are found in the context of a hidden treasure of a Dacian nobleman.{{sfn|Makkay|1995|p=341}} The treasure comprised 2 kilograms of gold ornaments; a helmet, necklace, appliqués, harness, and buttons for vestments. They were ceremonial ensemble for kings or noblemen and their horses.{{sfn|Sîrbu|2004|pp=46, 47}} The bracelets and necklace terminate with [[protome]]s of horse heads and exhibit strong Thracian roots.{{sfn|Sîrbu|2004|p=47}}

The heads have also been interpreted as goat-heads ([[ibex]]).{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}} Each head is very made of embossed gold foil with a filigree composition,{{sfn|Burda|1979|p=30}} and had sun-symbols on the middle of the forehead. They also have what may be seen as ram's- or goats-horns (see picture "''Head 1''" on the right).{{sfn|Sanie|1995|p=151}} These Băiceni gold artworks of the 4th century BC are viewed as one of the links transferring the Thracian and North Thracian Art forms and motifs across to the Dacian silversmiths.{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=27}}

== Iron Age II (La Tene) ==
Dacians replaced gold, the popular Transylvanian metal during the Iron Age I period, with silver during Iron Age II.{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=187}} The types of ornaments also changed, perhaps due to new social structures and hierarchy or due to changes of the preferences of the populous and [[sacerdotal]] aristocracy.{{sfn|Sîrbu|2004|p=54}}

Dacians absorbed influences from the western Celts and eastern Scythians, but also proved their artistic originality.{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=540}} The bracelet style of the former is more individual, as they synthesized the older local elements originating from the Bronze Age into a new combination adapted to include the contemporary decorative forms and motifs.{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=540}}

Objects specific to warriors (armors, harnesses etc.) became preponderant from the 5th century BC onwards, in contrast to the decorative objects (bracelets, torques and pendants) that predominated in the Bronze Age, and in the transition period leading up to the Iron Age.{{sfn| Gramatopol | 1992|p= 1}} In the 2nd and 1st centuries BC gold and silver military objects are replaced so that the treasures of the late Dacian La Tene comprise ceremonial ensembles of silver ornaments and clothing accessories, bracelets along with some [[Typology of Greek vase shapes|mastos or footed cup]] vases .{{sfn|Sîrbu| 2007| p= 864}}{{sfn|Sîrbu| 2004| p=54}}

The geometrical and spiral motif ornamentation of earlier bracelets is more often replaced with zoomorphic and vegetal representations.{{sfn| Gramatopol | 1992|p= 1}} The decorations of bracelets that have been found, across the whole territory inhabited by Dacians, consist of lines cut into fir-tree shapes, dots, circlets, [[palmette]]s, waves, and bead motifs.{{sfn|Daicoviciu|1971|p=63}}

=== Toteşti bracelet ===
[[File:Gold snake-head bracelet Totesti-Hateg.jpg|thumb|left|Snake-headed Dacian bracelet from [[Totesti]]. Transitional Hallstatt-La Tene period{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=546}}]]
Various single-spiral bracelets made of solid quadrangular (rhombic) gold bars, whose overlapping ends represent the head of a snake, were found in 1889 at [[Toteşti]] in [[Hunedoara County]].{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=545}}{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=339}} The head is geometrically stylized but clearly defined by decorative details. This artifact belongs to the so-called "Classic Dacian" period{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=339}} and described as a "primitive work done by a not skilful hand".{{citation needed|date=August 2011}} It was noted that the snake head is realistically depicted by the representation of the eyes, ears and other elements of the [[vipera ammodytes]] that is so commonly found in the area. The same scholars related these gold circlets to the later silver multi-spirals snake [[protome]] and palmette bracelets from [[Romos|Vaidei-Romos]], [[Bălăuşeri|Senereuş]], [[Hetur]], [[Marca, Sălaj|Marca]] and [[Oradea Mare]].{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=545}} Other scholars consider that [[Toteşti]] snake-headed ornaments should be interpreted on the basis of an abstract contemporary stylistic type, and not as an imitation of reality. In this interpretation [[Toteşti]] bracelets are not connected with the snakes from the region of Deva, but they are a tradition that began in Hallstatt times with the "Scythian rings" and continued into the La Tène period.{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=546}}

In the [[Scythian tombs]] of Northern Hungary that are related to the Scythian invasions from around 700 BC, as well as in those of central Romania, spiral-shaped rings known as the "Scythian rings" have been found; with one end forming a fantastic animal, such as a dragon or serpent. These apotropaic creatures, themselves [[Turano-Siberian]] varieties of old [[Mesopotamian monsters]], might have provided the model for the Dacian protome bracelet from [[Toteşti]]{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=58}}—but neither the Scythian animals nor the Greek decorations appear to have had great success in Dacia, since the native geometric style continued to predominate.{{sfn|Henry|1928|p=288}}

Analogies to the Totesti bracelets can be found not only to the multi-spiral bracelets, but also in the overlapping-end bracelets whose ends  sometimes terminate with stylized animal heads.{{sfn| Popescu | 1956|p= 227}}

=== Common Dacian types of the La Tene IB (250–150 BC) ===
{{multiple image
|image1=Dacian bracelet type Slimnic2.jpg|width1=200|caption1=Silver Dacian bracelet from Transylvania, found also at [[Slimnic]]{{sfn|Popescu|1948|p=54}}
|image2=Dacian bracelet type Slimnic5.jpg|width2=177|caption2=Silver Dacian bracelet from Transylvania, found also at [[Slimnic]]{{sfn|Popescu|1948|p=54}}
}}
The archaeological findings dated to this period of time comprise the following  types:
* One-spiral bracelet made of bar with engraved ends (mostly [[Hatching]] and [[Zigzag]]){{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=542-543}}
* Bracelets with non-joined ends. It originates from Bronze Age i.e. from [[Spalnaca]] type {{sfn|Popescu|1948|p=54}} {{sfn|Turcu|1979|p=153}}
* Bracelet made of bar having a plastic decoration of a Celtic type "S", i.e. [[Gyoma]]{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=542-543}}
* Bracelets with overlapped ends (i.e. [[Slimnic]] (Sibiu County) and [[Sâncrăieni]] (Harghita County).{{sfn|Popescu|1948|p=54}} {{sfn|Turcu|1979|p=153}} These are artifacts of local Hallstattian tradition originating from the first period of the Iron Age, and preserved until the late La Tene period.{{sfn| Szekely | 1965|p=57}}{{sfn|Turcu| 1979|p=153}} Analogous models dated to the late Hallstatt period have been found at [[Gogoşu, Mehedinţi|Balta Verde]] and [[Gogoşu, Mehedinţi|Gogosu]] (both in Mehedinti County).{{sfn| Szekely | 1965|p=57}}
* Bracelets with slightly widened or thickened ends.{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}}
* Multi-spirals bracelet found with [[Slimnic]] treasure.{{sfn|Vauthey|Vauthey|1968|p=345}} This is a re-adaptation of the older Carpathian spiral bracelet, earlier forms of it have been found in Bronze Age deposits at [[Gogoşu, Mehedinţi|Balta Verde]] and [[Gogoşu, Mehedinţi|Gogoşu]] (Mehedinti County).{{sfn|Turcu|1979|p=153}} This type could be considered as being just a simple form of the multi-spiral with protomes and palmettes.{{sfn|Szekely|1965|p=57}}
{{Clear}}

== Bracelets in the "Classical Dacian" period of the Dacian State ==
The Dacian silver bracelet is one of the characteristic artworks of this period, and the most representative ornament on them is the snake protome.{{sfn|MacKenzie|1986|p=87}}{{sfn|Popescu|1959|p=22}} Dacian bracelets have mainly been thought of as women's adornments but it can not be excluded that some types of bracelets, especially the multi-spirals ones, represented insignia of politico-military and [[sacerdotal]] functions and therefore worn by men.{{sfn | Berindei | Candea | 2001|p=749}}

Bracelets became part of the objects that Dacians selected as votive offerings deposited outside settlements. Such offerings have been found in a fountain at [[Ciolanestii din Deal]], Teleorman County, where silver bracelets and vases dated to 2nd or 1st century BC were found, and finds beside a lake in a forest at [[Contesti, Argeş|Contesti]], Argeş County, where bracelets, pearls, and a [[drachma]] were found.{{sfn|Sârbu|2007|p=862}}

Types of the La Tene II  period (150 BC – 100 AD) include:
* Bracelets with the ends curled back around the bracelet's wire i.e. [[Cerbal]] (Hunedoara County) and Remetea (Timis County){{sfn|Popescu|1948|p=54}} {{sfn|Turcu|1979|p=153}}
* Bracelets made of multiple twisted wires i.e. at [[Cerbăl]]{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=542-543}} In the La Tène Age, this type appears to have been developed from the twisted types of the Bronze Age IV from Spalnaca.{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=550}}
* Bracelets with double torsade i.e. [[Cerbăl]]{{sfn| Spanu | 2003|p=11}}
* Bracelets made of decorated band with circles and dotted lines i.e. [[Cerbăl]]{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=542-543}}
* Bracelets made of ribbed bar{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=542-543}}
* Bracelets with single- or multi-spirals terminating with snake heads{{sfn|MacKenzie|1986|p=87}}

