=== Regional finds ===
According to Horedt (1973), silver Dacian treasure finds can be typologically categorized into north and south groups, divided by the [[Târnava River]]. In the contact zone between them the artifacts are common to both zones.{{sfn|Rustoiu|2002|p=97}} In this classification the silver multi-spiral bracelets that are ornamented with palmettes and snake protomes would belong to the southern group.{{sfn|Rustoiu|2002|p=97}}

==== East of the Carpathian Mountains ====
The Dacian bracelets that have been found East of the Carpathians can be categorized into two main types:
* Non-joined ends i.e. those found at [[Poiana, Galaţi|Poiana]] (Galati County) and Gradistea ([[Brăila County]]). Numerous specimens are made of bronze, such as those found at Brad, Racatau and Poiana.{{sfn|Rustoiu|2002|p=102}}{{sfn|Condraticova|2010|p=117}}
* Overlapped ends that are coiled onto the wire itself.{{sfn|Rustoiu|2002|p=102}} {{sfn|Condraticova|2010|p=117}} This type has ornamentation consisting of geometrical motifs and sometimes of snake protomes.{{sfn|Condraticova|2010|p=117}}

The characteristic metals used for bracelets found in the area of the [[Siret River]] valley are bronze and iron,{{sfn|Rustoiu|2002|p=102}} though silver was also probably used; a silver bracelet was found with a treasure of coins buried after 119–122 AD.{{sfn|Rustoiu|2002|p=97}}

In the Prut-Dniester region sub-types have been  identified such as:
* Bronze bracelets such as those found at [[Trebujeni]], [[Maşcăuţi]] and [[Hansca]]
* Non-joined ends, bar with vegetal décor such as those from [[Tudora, Ştefan Vodă|Palanca-Tudora]]
* Bracelets made of 3–6 twisted bronze wires with flattened ornaments in the middle.{{sfn|Condraticova|2010|p=118}}
* Multi-spiral types, such as the bracelets from the treasure found at [[Mateuţi]] ([[Rezina District]]) dated to the 4th century BC. This treasure includes two silver bracelets, one with five spirals and one with three.{{sfn| Arnăut|Naniu|1996| p= 44}}

==== Moesia Superior ====
Dacian bracelets have been found in deposits from [[Tekija (Kladovo)|Tekija]], [[Bare (Požarevac)|Bare]],{{sfn|Popović|2004|p=41}} [[Veliko Središte]]{{sfn| Mărghitan | 1979|p= 164}} and [[Paraćin]].{{sfn|Kolaric|1970|p=22}}

The style and type of the bracelets from Tekija and Bare are similar to the Dacian silver types; i.e. bracelets made of twisted wire and bracelets with overlapped ends that are coiled around the wire itself.{{sfn|Popović|2004|p=41}} Even though the origins of this type should not necessarily be located in Dacia itself, since bracelets of this type are scattered throughout the entire Balkan-Danube area, the earliest dated bracelets from Tekija and Bare are very large, as were those typical of the Dacian cultural complex.{{sfn|Popović|2004|p=42}} Bracelets with ends shaped as a head of, or tail of, a serpent are well represented in the Dacian deposits that are found at the Bare.{{sfn|Popović|2004|p=42}}

The Dacian bracelets that are decorated with spiral end-pieces, i.e. Belgrad—[[Guberevac (Leskovac)]], along with thin Dacian silver necklaces found in East Serbia, characterize the presence of a Dacian La Tene culture at [[Paraćin]] in Serbia.{{sfn|Kolaric|1970|p=22}}

