=== Bracelets with cord ornaments ===
An important category of the jewelry in the Daco-Getic environment are bronze bracelets with cord ornaments, whose typology consists of three types held in the Blaj Museum and in Simleul Silvaniei. Such [[circlet]]s had been discovered at Ardeu, Cuciulata (Brasov), Costesti (Hunedoara), Ocnita (Valcea), Pecica (Arad), Simleul Silvaniei (Sălaj), Tilisca (Sibiu) and in the Orăstie Mountains.{{sfn| Plantos | 2005|p=77}} These ornaments do not seem to be specific to pre-Roman Dacia, as they were widely spread in contemporary Germany, Poland, Czech, Slovakia, Hungary and Slovenia—all during the La Tene period.{{sfn| Plantos | 2005|p=78}} Since their diameter is around 10&nbsp;cm, apart from those found in Simleul Silvaniei and Orăstie which are 6&nbsp;cm and 7.5&nbsp;cm, they were probably worn on the arm or as anklets.{{sfn| Plantos | 2005|p=79}} They have been found mainly in fortresses or important centers of pre-Roman Dacia, and appear to have been prestige items of the local aristocracy.{{sfn| Plantos | 2005|p=79}}

=== Bracelets with a double torsade ===
This type have been found with treasures from Cerbăl (Hunedoara County), Bistrita (Bistriţa-Năsăud County), [[Drăgeşti]] (Bihor County), [[Oradea-Sere]] (Bihor County), [[Saracsău]] (Alba County), and [[Tilişca]] (Sibiu County). The bracelets are made of wire turned two or three times to form a semicircular terminal. The three-turns style is seen only with a single bracelet from Cerbăl. These terminals are always decorated with stamped-dotted lines and are dated to the 1st century BC.{{sfn| Spanu | 2003|p=11}}

This type was designed and preferred by the intra-Carpathian regions. Only one presence occurs in the Danube area, at Iron Gates.{{sfn| Spanu | 2003|p=12}} Since this bracelet appears to have been a prestige ornament, its presence south of the Carpathians is seen as a component of the relationships between the elites of the two neighboring regions.{{sfn| Spanu | 2003|p=12}}

=== The material of bracelets ===
[[File:KunsthistorischesMuseumDacianGold3.jpg|thumb|right| Dacian silver ornaments ([[Kunsthistorisches Museum]])]]
[[File:KunsthistorischesMuseumDacianGold6.jpg|thumb|right|Silver Dacian treasures (dated to La Tene) found in Transylvania Romania (Kunsthistorisches Museum)]]

In the Bronze Age IV and Hallstatt periods Dacia was characterized by gold treasures and by a particular gold art, whereas archaeological finds dated to the La Tene period are mostly made of silver.{{sfn| Popescu | 1956|p= 244}}{{sfn|Glodariu|Sima|Iaroslavschi|Gheorghiu|2008|p=146}} This is a common characteristic of the Illyrian and Eastern Alps regions of the time, and not limited to the Dacian area.{{sfn| Popescu | 1956|p= 244}} Some scholars, such as Glodariu, explain the scarcity of gold ornaments and bracelets in Dacian treasures by a custom of the Dacians, Celts, Germans and Romans in reserving golden ornaments for the king alone.{{sfn|Glodariu|Sima|Iaroslavschi|Gheorghiu|2008|p=146}} Other scholars, such as Florescu, put forth the hypothesis of religious restrictions regarding the use of gold in the period of the Dacian state.{{sfn|Florescu|1970|p=135}}

The golden Dacian bracelets, and indeed most of the jewelry, that has been found so far are made of unrefined gold from the [[Apuseni Mountains]].{{sfn|Oberländer-Târnoveanu|Gheorghe|Migdonia|Tudor|2010|p=9}}

The silver of the Dacian bracelets and other ornaments of the time always contain between 0.63 and 6.35% gold.{{sfn|Seculici|2008|p=69}} In some scholars opinions, such as Oberländer-Târnoveanu, it was obtained by melting Greek and Roman coins as well as importing from Balkan sources.{{sfn|Oberländer-Târnoveanu|Gheorghe|Migdonia|Tudor|2010|p=9}} Others, Popescu for example, support the thesis of a local extraction of silver from the Apuseni Mountains.{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=197}}

The work and typology of the silver multi-spirals snake-headed bracelets suggests the existence of a large manufacturing center, located most probably near the Dacian sites of the [[Orastie Mountains]].{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=188}} From there silver artifacts spread throughout the entire area of modern-day Transylvania; and, as archaeological finds prove, these art works become later known in areas that encompass the modern regions of [[Moldavia]], [[Muntenia]] and [[Oltenia]].{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=188}}

In the second phase of La Tène, reasoned on the basis of finds, Dacia appears to have experienced a temporary "silver crisis", probably related to an increase in the minting of silver [[denarii]]; therefore, bracelets dated to that time had been made of mild alloy and only plated with a silver layer about 0.1&nbsp;mm (0.004&nbsp;inch) thick. The layer was so well welded that the welding can not be identified by the naked eye, even in cross sections.{{sfn|Glodariu|1997|p=25}} Specimens of the group include finds from [[Sarmasag]] (Salaj County) and [[Dersca]] (Botosani County). There were also similar finds at [[Slimnic]] (Sibiu County) and Herastrau Bucuresti.{{sfn|Rustoiu|1996|p=47}}
[[File:KunsthistorischesMuseumDacianGold1.jpg|thumb|left|A gilded silver belt fragment Cioara – Alba County dated [[La Tene]] depicts warriors wearing bracelets{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=532}}]]

=== Representations depicting the wearing of Dacian bracelets ===
The Dacian phalera from [[Cergău|Lupu-Cergău, Alba County]], depicts a feminine divinity wearing some circlets on her arms. Some scholars identified these with a representation of the Dacian bracelet types.{{sfn|Spânu|1998|p=49}}{{sfn|Crișan|1993|p=45}}

In 1820 at [[Săliştea|Cioara (today Săliştea)]] a fragmentary gilded silver plaque was discovered, dated to La Tène III, and primitively decorated ''[[au repousse]]'' ("by embossing"), with representations of two human characters, probably warriors.{{sfn|Oltean|2007|p=106}} Hatched bands are visible on the arms and wrists  that resemble regular bracelets.{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=16}} Even though the motifs of the plaque do not seem to be local, since it differs in some respects from those depicted on [[Trajan's Column]], the silver-work itself seems to be Dacian. Other than the Dacians, no-one was working in this style at that time. The silversmith who made it is probably the same one who made the well known Dacian snake-headed bracelets from Hunedoara County.{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=534}}

A fragment from the Forum of Roman Emperor Trajan (2nd century AD) in Rome has a relief of a seated female, probably a Dacian (''Dacia Capta'' – "the conquered Dacia"). She is depicted wearing a bracelet on each arm below the shoulder.{{sfn|Packer|Sarring |1997|p=377}}

===Bracelets with a snake-motif===
This motif is found with both the multi-spiral bracelets and also with the simple bracelets.{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=641}}
[[File:Dacian bracelet type Slimnic1.jpg|thumb|left|Dacian bracelet from Transylvania; [[Slimnic]] type (La Tene Age){{sfn|Popescu|1948|p=54}}]]

* Multi-spiral silver bracelets terminating with portions of [[palmette]]s and snake [[protome]] terminals at each end, i.e. those found at [[Cojocna]], [[Mărunţei|Bălăneşti (Mărunţei)]], [[Rociu]], [[Coada Malului]]{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}}{{sfn| Spanu |Cojocaru|2009|p=99}} [[Caţa|Drauseni (Caţa)]] (destroyed by 1941),{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=198}} [[Feldioara]] and [[Orastie]].{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=196}} The endings of some of the bracelets were gilded: i.e. [[Coada Malului]] {{sfn|Vauthey|Vauthey|1968|p=346}} and [[Orastie]].{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=196}}
* Multi-spiral bracelets with snake-heads at each terminal, but whose terminals do not have the palmettes, that are plaques decorated with large scales, i.e. those from [[Herastrau|Herastrau (Bucuresti)]] dated to the 1st century BC.{{sfn| Spanu |Cojocaru|2009|p=99}} A bracelet from [[Buneşti-Avereşti|Bunesti]] ([[Vaslui County]]) is similar to the one from Herastrau, but it is dated earlier than the 1st century BC.{{sfn| Bazarciuc |1983|p= 264}}
* Simple bracelets, where stylized snake heads terminate the ends.{{sfn|Florescu|Daicoviciu|Roşu|1980|p=68}} The ends are either in the shape of an animal's head summarily but adroitly stylized, as in the case of the [[Slimnic]] bracelets, or in other cases the animal's head is suggested by a few engraved lines, and the decorated ends were gilded.{{sfn|Popescu|1971|p=45}} Finds include those from: [[Ocnita]] (Valcea County),{{sfn|Rustoiu|1996|p=46}} [[Poiana, Galaţi|Poiana]] (Tecuci),{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=201}} Săcălăsău Nou (Bihor County),{{sfn|Gorun|Doina|Sever|Lucia|1988|p=116}} in Romania; and also from [[Jakabszállás]] in Hungary.{{sfn|Toma|2007|p=66}}
* Bronze bracelets cast and incised with snake [[protome]]s, i.e. those found in [[Râşnov]], [[Braşov County]], and dated to the 2nd or 1st century AD.{{sfn|Costea|2008|p=1}}

==== Description of the silver multi-spiral bracelets with palmettes and protomes at both terminals ====
There are about 27 known Dacian silver or silver-gilt multi-spiral bracelets terminating with rectangular plaques and snake head [[protome]]s. They are exhibited or kept in repositories and museums in Bucharest (Romania), Budapest (Hungary) and Belgrade (Serbia).{{sfn|Constantinescu|2009|p=1031}} Additionally the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] holds Dacian silver bracelets such as the one found at [[Orastie]] (Hunedoara County){{sfn| Candea| 2010|p= 52}} and the one from Feldioara (Brasov County).{{sfn| Candea| 2010|p= 52}}{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=21}}
[[File:Dacian Silver Bracelet at the National Museum of Romanian History 2011.jpg|thumb|left| Silver bracelet from [[Rociu]] ([[Arges County]])]]

All of these silver works are characterized by their large size. For example, the one found at [[Bălăuşeri|Senereuş]], now in the [[Brukenthal Museum]] weights aropund 0.4 kilograms (0.88 pounds). The wire used is 206&nbsp;cm (6 feet 9&nbsp;inches) long and 0.4&nbsp;cm (0.157&nbsp;inches) thick, while the heads are 21&nbsp;cm each (8.26&nbsp;inches). The inside diameter of the coils is 12.5&nbsp;cm (4.92&nbsp;inches) with an outside diameter of 13.3&nbsp;cm (5.2&nbsp;inches). These large diameters and the heavy weight of these armlets would suggest wearing them on the upper arm or on the leg.{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=548}}{{sfn|Oberländer-Târnoveanu|2011|RAN ID=115691.01}} The coils of the specimen from [[Cluj Napoca]] have an even bigger outside diameter at 16&nbsp;cm (6.3&nbsp;inches);{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=196}} therefore, it is supposed that it was worn on the thigh or forearm over clothes{{sfn|Popescu|1971|p=45}}

The specimen from the Transylvanian Museum at Cluj weighs 0.358 kilograms (0.79 pounds). It has been made by hammering a silver bar of a circular cross-section. It has 4 spirals and the ends are flattened, decorated with seven palmettes made by punching. The surfaces of the palmettes, and their extremities, are decorated with the "fir-tree" motif and incised circles.{{sfn|Pupaza|2010|p=1}}

The multi-spiral from Belgrad Museum has an interesting particularity in that the impression of the palmette motif has two [[puncheon (barrel)|puncheon]]s of different dimensions. This might have been done in order to avoid the stereotypy of models.{{sfn| Mărghitan | 1979|p= 164}}

===== Origins =====
Snakes are depicted in Dacian toreutics from the 6th and 5th centuries BC, and also in the later period.{{sfn | Sanie| 1995|p=145}} Both types of bracelets with snake protomes, those of simple and multiple spirals, show an ancient Thracian tradition from the Hallstatt period (the Geto-Thracian period) of Geto-Dacian art evolution.{{sfn|Berciu|1974|p=217}} Snake-shaped bracelets, and other ornaments of the same kind, speak not only of the spread of the decorative motif but also of a symbol and significance of this motif in the Dacian period.{{sfn|Ispas|1980|p=279}}

Some scholars suppose that the Scythians provided the model of the snake décor found in the Classical Dacian bracelets, on the basis that the semi-spiraled Scythian snake type rings, were common in Dacia after the Hallstatt period. Those rings might have been continuously used until the La Tène period, or perhaps until the Roman era, as can be seen with a necropolis from [[Roşia, Sibiu|Caşolţ]], Sibiu County.{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=641}}{{sfn| Banateanu| 1971|p=38}} If this was the case, Shchukin suggests it was a matter of transferred ideas rather than of imports.{{sfn| Shchukin| 1989|p=89}}

These bracelets types can be explained by the typology of the local tradition of the Hallstattian period; and there were similar bracelets in the Thracian world of today's Romania and Bulgaria.{{sfn|Berciu|1974|p=217}}{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=27}} Such examples include a mid-3rd-century BC spiral dragon-headed ring; a spiral snake-headed ring from [[Nesebar|Nesebar (Messembria)]]; 4th century BC spiraled bracelets from [[Aitos]]; and a 3rd-century BC snake-headed ring of unknown origin in the British Museum.{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=27}}

The manufacture of the spirals, by wrapping the silver wire several times, belongs to the traditions of the Bronze Age;{{sfn|Henry|1928|p=290}} but those with their ends flattened, and decorated on the outside with [[intaglio (jewellery)|intaglio]] palmettes, belong to a more modern style according to Popescu.{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=193}} The way in which these dragon patterned bracelets were developed by the Dacians was new, while its resemblance to the workmanship and style of other countries are so few, that these bracelets might very well be considered as specifically Dacian. It can be distinguished as a Dacian style since they remained faithful to their own geometric representations,{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=141}} and the palmette motif is not found in the neighboring areas.{{sfn | Mărghitan | 1979|p=164}}

