==== The dragon and snake-head motif ====
Within the multi-spiral  group of bracelets with palmette scales, two sub-groups can be stylistically identified – one represented by the Feldioara find and the other by the Orastie find. These sub-groups show that the snake and dragon types were not absolutely immutable in the imagination of the Dacian silversmiths. Two variants were introduced: mammal head – snake head and crest – mane,{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=27}} as well as some transitional versions.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=22}}
[[File:Dacians bearing the draco on Trajan's Column.jpg|thumb|right| The Dacian symbol [[Dacian Draco]] as depicted on the [[Trajan's Column]]]]
[[File:Dacian bracelet-ends snake-heads.jpg|thumb|left|Details of the "dragon" head of both ends; Silver bracelets from [[Hetur]], [[Romos|Vaidei (Romos)]] and [[Darlos]] Romania{{sfn|Hampel|1888|p=278}}]]

The bracelet discovered around 1856 at [[Orăștie]] consists of a single silver wire, with a circular cross-section, coiled into eight equal spirals terminating in a dragon head at both ends. It is analogous to the bracelet from Feldioara but its head is different in that the head is almost triangular.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=25}} It has been made in a richer figurative manner than others.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=14}}

The multi-spiral bracelet with zoomorphic (snake?) ends, found in 1859 with a treasure from [[Feldioara]], is different because of the widened muzzle of the [[protome]] terminals. In the middle of the snake head the Dacian silversmith engraved braids, by the use of puncheons, consisting of two rows of small, oblique, divergent traits. The snake's eyes are depicted as two circles. A strong profile separates the head from a relatively rectangular plaque with rounded corners, and slightly arched edges representing the mane of the [[Dacian Draco|Dacian dragon]]. The profiled relief edges of the bracelet's rectangular plaque and its decoration with two rows of divergent slashes are suggestive of the mane of a dragon or wolf.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=87}}

The bracelets from the Museum of Transylvania found in Cluj, Hetiur ([[Mureș County]]) and [[Ghelința]] are characterized by a more [[wikt:trenchant|trenchant]] cutting and a more prominent relief for modeling the head. These traits are unlikely to represent a specific ophidian form and the longitudinal axis is marked by a stylistically different means.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=22}}

The zoomorphic motif of the bracelets depicts a fantastic animal with the head and body of a serpent but the muzzle of a mammal, pointed or square, with a thick mane flowing on its back prolonged by a poly-lobed (multiple palmettes) body. {{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=87}}{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=141}} The analysis of these Dacian symbols, performed by scholars—such as Florescu (1979), Pârvan (1926), and Bichir (1984)—conclude that the symbol of the snake or dragon appears on the Geto-Dacian La Tene bracelets and on the [[Dacian Draco|Dacian standard (flag)]] that can be seen on [[Trajan's Column]].{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=87}}{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=141}}{{sfn|Bichir|1984|p=54}} The Dacians dragon probably combines two meanings: the agility and redoubtable ferocity of the wolf with the protective role of the snake.{{sfn|Sârbu|2000|p=170}} It was supposed to encourage the [[Getae]] and to scare their enemies.{{sfn| Sirbu | 1997|p= 89}} It also appeared to have been the only one known representation of the religious character of the Dacians of the time.{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=641}} Scholastic interpretations vary between considering this a representation of a "flying dragon", related to a [[Sky God]],{{sfn|Pârvan|1926|p=520}} or a [[chthonic]] symbol.{{sfn|Tutilă|2004|p=5}}

Some bracelets from south of the Carpathians, such as those from [[Coada Malului]], [[Dâmbovița County|Bălăneşti]] and [[Rociu]]; and some from north of the Carpathians such as those from [[Dârlos]] and [[Romos|Vaidei (Romos)]]) do not have decorative elements to mark the median line on the rectangular plaque (the wider and flat portion coming next to the head). They instead have wavy lines, finely engraved, suggesting a mane or ridge.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=26}} A similar style is seen in specimens from [[Bălăuşeri|Senereuş]], [[Dupuş]] (Sibiu County) and from the unknown Transylvanian site, the fragment of which is kept at the Budapest Museum. On the latter, the beam of wavy lines has been replaced by horizontal, short and dense, finely engraved lines.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=26}}

The rectangular portion of the bracelets from Bălăneşti and Transylvania show a tendency to split into two teardrop-shaped lobes.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=26}} On the subgroup of bracelets from [[Coada Malului]], the fir-tree is depicted only schematically.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=26}}

It was also noted that the snakes from the Agighiol artifacts of the 4th century BC, especially the depicted heads of snakes, have a stylization similar to that of the Dacian bracelet protomes; they have the same triangular form, and the same distribution of the decorations that mark the eye of the snake.{{sfn|Berciu|1974|p=217}}

====The leaf motifs of the multi-spiral bracelets====
[[File:Palmettes of Dacian silver bracelet.jpg|thumb|left|Detail: the fir-tree motif and the rectangular portion of the silver bracelet (1st century BC) repository [[Cluj-Napoca]] Museum{{sfn| Pupeză |2010|p=1}}]]
[[File:Palmettes of Dacian bracelets Kunsthistorisches.jpg|thumb|left|Detail, palmette motif of the bracelet from Orastie (1st century BC)]]
[[File:Peretu Helmet side view Muzeul National de Istorie al Romaniei.jpg|thumb|right|Palmettes on 4th-century BC helmet (some bracelets have similar palmette as the Agighiol helmet{{sfn|Berciu|1974|p=210}})]]

The flattened bands of the bracelets are decorated externally with a chain of geometrized palmettes that have been struck in much the same way as coins.{{sfn|Pârvan|Vulpe|1928|p=141}} It seems that the leaf-like ornaments have been made by impression, using ready-made moulds, as used in the manufacture of Dacian cups from the La Tène [[Balaciu|Crasani (com. Balaciu)]] site. Scholars, such as Popescu, related the chain of successive palmettes of the Dacian bracelets to the decoration of the borders on the Scythian Melgunov dagger sheath from the 6th century BC.{{sfn|Popescu|1941|p=193}} Others consider that several multi-spiral bracelets, i.e. from [[Mărunţei|Balanesti]] (Olt), have the same palmette motif as the typical decorations of the 4th-century BC Thracian-Getic helmet from [[Valea Nucarilor|Agighiol (com. Valea Nucarilor)]], [[Tulcea]].{{sfn|Berciu|1974|p=210}} In the opinion of Berciu, the palmette motif was adopted from the Greeks of the Black Sea coast during the Geto-Thracian Art period.{{sfn|Berciu|1974|p=217}}

Dacian bracelets exhibit four decorative types of leaf-like triangular lobes: first is the most complex is of oval or triangular palmettes; the second is interpreted as representing fern leaves (e.g. the Orastie bracelet); the third is the fir-tree motif, where the rounded lobes become straight lines resembling a fir-tree branch; and the fourth whose shape preserves only the medial [[Leaf#Veins|vein]] and the circles, suggesting the spiral arching of the lobes (e.g. the Feldioara bracelet).{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=87}}

The palmettes are more precisely outlined and more faithfully preserve the original lobes and palmette character, with several bracelets such as those from the Cluj Museum, Hetiur and Ghelinta. They are farthest away from a schematic fir-tree motif.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=22}} A stylized ivy leaf-like style is common to the group of bracelets from Coada Malului, Rociu and Bălăneşti ([[Arges County]]), and Dupuş. It is formed using carved lines doubled with a fine series of dots.{{sfn|Florescu |Miclea |1979|p=27}}

===== The same motif seen in other ornaments =====
The decorative snake style has been adopted in other types of ornaments, such as earrings from [[Blandiana|Răcătău]] and spiral rings from [[Sprâncenata]] and [[Mihăileşti|Popeşti-Novaci]].{{sfn|Sîrbu|Florea| 2000|p=169}}

The silver ring from [[Măgura, Teleorman]] has four-and-a-half multi-spirals with snake-head terminals and a chain of five palmettes.{{sfn|Mirea|2008|p=1}} It belongs to a small silver treasure—comprising three [[denarii]] that could be dated between 148–106 BC, and one ornament (the ring) —fortuitously discovered in 2005 and 2006 in a spot 330&nbsp;m from Măgura village.{{sfn|Mirea|2009|p=99}} The ring is considered by some, e.g. Mirea (2009), to be a miniaturized representation of the typical multi-spiral bracelets terminating with palmettes and snake protomes.{{sfn|Mirea|2009|p=100}} There are particular analogies with the bracelets from Bălăneşti–Olt and Rociu–Argeş; as well as analogies with the spiral rings from Sprâncenata and Popeşti.{{sfn|Mirea|2009|p=100}} The decorations are similar to a motif of the gold multi-spiral bracelets discovered in 1999–2001 at [[Sarmizegetusa Regia]].{{sfn|Mirea|2009|p=100}}

====Significance and archaeology of the silver multi-spiral bracelets with palmettes and protomes====
[[File:Dacian ornaments multi spirals palmettes and protome.jpg|thumb|right| Locations of the 1st-century BC to 1st-century AD multi-spirals with protome and palmettes ornaments' finds .{{sfn|Spânu|Cojocaru|2009|p=111}}{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=21}}{{sfn|Mirea|2009|p=100}}]]
[[File:Transylvanian silver snake-headed bracelet (Ancient Dacia).JPG|thumb|left|Silver snake-headed multi-spirals bracelet 1st century BC to 1st century AD (Transylvania, Romania).{{sfn|Hampel|1888|p=278}}]]

The multi-spiral bracelets made of plates with zoomorphic extremities, all of them made of silver and sometimes gilded, are characteristic of the north-Danubian Dacian elite, in particular ones from Transylvania.{{sfn|Arsenescu|Sirbu|2006|p=170}} Also, according to Medelet (1976), one Dacian silver bracelet from [[Malak Porovets]] ([[Isperih Municipality]] Bulgaria) and one Dacian silver bracelet from [[Velika Vrbica]] (Serbia), belong to the same typology.{{sfn|Spânu|Cojocaru|2009|p=111}} Some of this type of bracelets, such as the one in the [[Cluj-Napoca Transilvanias History Museum]] and the two others in the National Museum Budapest (Hungary), are from unknown Transylvanian sites.{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=27}}

It is possible the big silver multi-spirals were used with clothes worn for special celebrations,{{sfn|Sîrbu|Florea| 2000|p=169}} though they do not seem to have a simply decorative use.{{sfn|Crișan|1986|p=26}} {{sfn| Sârbu |2007|p=864}} The context of burying these prestige aristocratic insignia suggests that the treasures they compound were rather votive deposits than funeral offerings ([[cenotaph]]?).{{sfn|Spânu|1998|p=52}}

The silver snake-headed multi-spiral bracelets are found in the context of the so-called Dacian silver treasures.{{sfn| Sârbu| Florea|1997|p=32}} A significant fact regarding these treasures is the specificity of the time frame, from around 125 BC – 25 AD (one century).{{sfn|Spânu|1998|p=46}} In historical terms, they are contemporary to the reigns of [[Burebista]], [[Deceneus]] and [[Comosicus]]. It is probable that the hoards of silver bracelets and ornaments of the late Geto-Dacian began to be produced just prior to the reign of [[Burebista]], a possible example being the one from Sâncrăieni. The manufacturing of silver ornaments continued during his reign, although to a lesser extent (perhaps due to his authoritarian, despotic and purist nature), and mostly after his suppression of the manufacture (44 BC – 46 AD); therefore the silver hoard production lasted almost a century.{{sfn|Gramatopol|2008|p=1}} The burying of these Dacian silver jewelry items and bracelets (those made between 44 BC and 46 AD) occurred in the same period of time that was characterized by a scarcity of silver due to the turbulent situation in Dacia.{{sfn|Gramatopol|2008|p=1}}

This particular type of design has a unitary typology and a highly standardized character. It does not contain goods that had been accumulated over years, but only sets of certain objects.{{sfn|Spânu|1998|p=46}} Also, they have not been found in the context of settlements but outside them, on carefully prepared deposits.{{sfn|Spânu|1998|p=47}} These objects had not been temporarily concealed or hidden, because of some exposure to dangerous situations, but they were rather supposed to preserve the symbolic attributes of the social status in the afterlife.{{sfn|Spânu|1998|p=49}}

Several Dacian bracelets reached the collections of the Kunsthistorisches Vienna Museum through various channels: administrative, auctions, purchases, and donations. Though they were found in Transylvania, and belong to the similar archaeological context of the other Dacian silver treasures, they are rather accidental discoveries from the west and south of the Transylvanian plateau—both in the areas of the greatest concentration of Dacian culture in the [[Orăştie Mountains|Orăştie]] and [[Apuseni Mountains]], where precious metal mineral deposits were, and are, to be found.{{sfn|Florescu|Miclea|1979|p=85}}

== Gold multi-spiraled dragon-headed and animal protome bracelets ==
[[File:Dacian Gold Bracelet at the National Museum of Romanian History 2011 - 4.jpg|thumb|eft|Gold bracelet from Sarmizegetusa Regia – 1st century BC (NMIR Museum Bucharest)]]
[[File:101 Conrad Cichorius, Die Reliefs der Traianssäule, Tafel CI.jpg|thumb|right|Romans taking valuable Dacian loot (Trajan's Column Scene CXXXVIII)]]
[[File:Bratara Dacica 3aa.jpg|thumb|left|Dacian gold bracelet from [[Sarmizegetusa Regia]]; dated to the 1st century BC {{sfn|Trohani|2007|p=1}}{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2010|p=1040}} ]]
[[File:Dacian Gold Bracelet at the National Museum of the Union 2007 - 1.jpg|thumb|left|Dacian gold bracelet, dated to the 1st century BC, from [[Sarmizegetusa Regia|Sarmizegetusa]] [[Romania]] {{sfn|Trohani|2007|p=5}}{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2010|p=1040}}]]
[[File:Dacian Bracelet IMG 7402.JPG|thumb|left|Dacians gold bracelet from Sarmizegetusa Regia]]

Gold artifacts in general, and gold bracelets in particular, have been scarce archaeological finds during excavations. An explanation could be that the Romans collected all gold objects by force after conquering Dacia.{{sfn|Manaila|1976|p=90}} Some, including Manaila, explained the scarcity of these kinds of archaeological finds as due to Dacian religious reasons, all gold being collected by the priests and given to the Dacian king.{{sfn|Manaila|1976|p=90}} Numerous researchers, including Rustoiu, argued the existence of a royal monopoly of the gold and silver exploitation in Dacia;{{sfn|Rustoiu|1996|p=51}} and that after the Roman conquest, this monopoly passed to the Roman Emperor.{{sfn|Popescu|1971|p=44}}

=== Description ===
These gold bracelets, adorned with leaves and snake heads, weigh around 2.2 pounds (1 kilogram) each.{{sfn|Watson|2011|p=1}} There are remarkable analogies between the gold armlets and those made of silver from [[Măgurele, Prahova|Coada Malului]] (Prahova County), Senereuş (Hunedoara County), [[Orăştie]] (Hunedoara County) and [[Herăstrău]]-[[Bucureşti]].{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2007|p=12}} Most of them exhibit similar design and artistic themes, but there are no two identical bracelets.{{sfn|Constantinescu|2008|p=1}}
The decorations on these bracelets is similar to the style of the ring from Magura ([[Teleorman County]]).{{sfn|Mirea|2009|p=100}}

One such bracelet recovered in 2007 has both terminals depicting a stylized animal head, which represents a snake with a long muzzle, and is decorated with arched lines. The rectangular plaque's surface is decorated with transverse rows of arched incisions, grouped in four and a half [[Metope (architecture)|metopes]]. The body is composed of seven palmettes, consisting of a fir tree-shape, and a dotted line in the middle, while the terminals oppose each other.{{sfn|Trohani |2007|p=1}}

The number of spirals varies from six to eight. When uncoiled, some bracelets measure 2.30 m and others 2.80 m. The outside diameters range from 91 to 123&nbsp;mm. The spirals consist of flat rectangular strips with richly incised decorations and stylized palmettes. In most of them, seven palmettes decorate both ends of the bracelets.{{sfn|Constantinescu|2009|p=1031}} The bracelets terminate with a decorative [[protoma]], a beast-head motif which looks like the head of an animal (a wolf, a snake or a dog).{{sfn|Constantinescu|2008|p=1}} The [[goldsmith]] technique, used for manufacturing all of these gold armlets, was the cold hammering of a rectangular-shaped gold ingot, followed by punching and engraving for their decorations. This was a typical method used by Dacians from the 4th century BC to 1st century AD.{{sfn|Constantinescu|2009|p=1031}}

A bracelet recovered in 2009 has ten spirals. The terminals depict a stylized snake protome. The long muzzle is straight cut and the eyes and eyebrows are represented by curved lines. The head continues onto a rectangular plaque of 3.4&nbsp;cm in length whose relief edges are decorated with incised oblique lines in a "V" shape, separated by a medial line. This is followed by a series of six triangular-oval palmettes, made by three puncheons, and with a length of 14.3&nbsp;cm. The first puncheon made the first two palmettes, the second made the next two palmettes, and the third was used for the last—which is also the smallest palmette. The palmettes have a foliage design and their edges are raised and decorated with small incised oblique lines.{{sfn|Trohani |2009|p=1}}

=== Context ===
[[File:Sarmizegetusa temples.jpg|thumb|right| Ruins of temple of the ancient [[Dacian language|Dacian]] fortress of Sarmizegetusa (Hunedoara County – Romania)]]
Some two dozen of the gold multi-spiral zoomorphic-headed bracelets were discovered by archaeological looting in different spots in the area of Sarmisegetusa Regia, in the Orăștie Mountains.{{sfn|Constantinescu|2009|p=1028}} By 2011, twelve out of the twenty-four looted gold bracelets had been recovered and are housed at the Romanian National History Museum in Bucharest.{{sfn|Watson|2011|p=1}}

An archaeological context has been reconstituted on the basis of a forensic science approach, technical description, and archaeological interpretation. The multi-spiral bracelets had been uncovered from pits near to the "Sacred area" of the Dacian capital at [[Sarmizegetusa Regia]] (Hunedoara County), around 600&nbsp;m from the sacred enclosure. The pits are located on the steep rocky slopes outside the ancient settlements, in a narrow valley.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2007|p=109}} The bracelets site is located on a very steep and rocky area that involves a difficult climb and hinders "classical" archaeological approaches and research.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2007|p=109}}

The treasure hunters discovered a spot where they found ten golden bracelets in a pit dug into natural rock on a 70° slope.{{sfn|Glodariu|Sima|Iaroslavschi|Gheorghiu|2008|p=146}}  The pit had two distinct overlapped cavities of triangular shape made of slabs, one containing six  gold multi-spiral bracelets and the other four, that had each been deposited in pairs; the smaller bracelets were inserted into the larger ones.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2007|p=99}} The finding of bracelets on such steep sloping cliffs, and at the outer limits (eastern) of the settlements, provides a new perspective regarding the ancient sites used for depositing artifacts with special religious significance.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2007|p=109}} These deposits are composed of the same type of ornaments that have identical function and significance.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2007|p=109}}

The general circumstances of the placement of these bracelets, deposited by the ancient populous, in these specially constructed pits and covered with uncut slabs imply that these artifacts were components of votive offerings.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2007|p=110}}{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2010|p=1040}} It seems as if these bracelets were used during initiations, or occult ceremonies, restricted to a certain category of people that had very important positions in the state: the king; the leaders of cities; the nobles from the royal entourage; and the priests.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2007|p=110}} This explains the existence of similar pieces made of silver for the leading nobles and rulers of the cities, and the lack of similar specimens made of bronze, iron or other metals. It also explains why these types of bracelet do not appear in written sources, nor the figurative representations of the time.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2007|p=110}}

=== Chronology and authentication ===
Based on typological analogy and stylistic analysis, historians believe that these bracelets are authentic Dacian artifacts.{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2007|p=11}} Some chronological evidence is provided by dark blotches that indicate a long period of time underground, and also by the ancient coins that were found along with bracelets. These coins point to the late 2nd century BC and the first decades of the 1st century BC. It appears that the bracelets were buried, if not necessarily crafted, during a time frame between 100 – 70 BC.{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2010|p=1040}}

The chronology of these bracelets corresponds to the emergence of the building of religious sanctuaries, digging and arranging pits with a religious purpose where deposits of offerings to the [[chthonic|chthonian]] gods had been made.{{sfn|Ciuta|Rustoiu|2010|p=110}}

In 2007 a compositional analysis of these gold objects was performed using a non-destructive method, [[particle-induced X-ray emission]] (micro-PIXE measurements) and synchrotron [[X-Ray fluorescence]] (SR-XRF) analysis.{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2007|p=26}} More studies were performed in 2008 and 2009 by a team consisting of members from the National Institute for Nuclear Physics and Engineering, Romania, the National History Museum of Romania, and the BAM Federal Institute for Materials Research and Testing, Germany. Researchers compared the gold composition, examining the trace [[platinum group]] elements, [[Tin]], [[Tellurium]], [[Antimony]], [[Mercury (element)|Mercury]], and [[Lead]] and comparing them with the corresponding elements of natural gold from [[Transylvania]]. This was done since these trace-elements are more significant for provenancing archaeological metallic-artifacts than the main element components.{{sfn|Constantinescu|2008|p=1}} For these studies, several small fragments of natural Transylvanian gold – placer and primary – were analyzed using: the micro-PIXE technique at the Legnaro National Laboratory AN2000 micro-beam facility, Italy, and at the AGLAE accelerator, C2RMF, Paris, France; and by using micro-synchrotron radiation X-ray fluorescence (micro-SR-XRF) at the BESSY synchrotron, Berlin, Germany.{{sfn|Constantinescu|2008|p=1}} The studies of the teams concluded that the gold multi-spiral bracelets found between 1999–2001 at Sarmizegethusa had been made of native Transylvanian gold and not refined gold.{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2007|p=26}}{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2010|p=1041}}

Because of the adverse conditions surrounding the hoard's discovery, their origins may never be authenticated to the full satisfaction of archaeologists and scientists.{{sfn|Watson|2011|p=1}} Sceptics suggest that the bracelets could have been produced in modern times from metal obtained by melting ancient gold coins, Dacian coins of the KOSON type or Greek Lysimachus coins; however, the analyses performed so far do not confirm the use of gold from these coins in the bracelets' manufacture.{{sfn|Constantinescu|Bugoi|Cojocaru|Niculescu|2010|p=1038}}

It is most likely that no other group of ancient goldwork has been more thoroughly examined by scientists, technologists and scholars in various countries and various institutions than the Dacian gold spirals with dragon terminals found between 1999–2001 at Sarmizegethusa. In each case-study, and completely independent from each other, their examinations led to the same conclusion.{{sfn|Deppert-Lippitz|2008|p=1}}

