{{Refimprove|date=September 2014}}

'''Hasina''' is the concept of [[sanctity]] and imbued authority in the traditional culture of [[Madagascar]]. An individual is believed to be imbued with ''hasina'', which can be augmented or diminished by their actions or by the tribute or authority conceded to them by others. Rulers in traditional society were the ultimate embodiment of ''hasina'', whereas community leaders and heads of families possessed relatively less. The same term, ''hasina'', was used to describe tributes given to political leaders, which in the 19th century [[Kingdom of Imerina]] typically took the form of a silver coin and accompanying prayer.<ref>[http://horizon.documentation.ird.fr/exl-doc/pleins_textes/divers4/010017390.pdf Hasina in Madagascar]</ref>

